    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-1770429">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-1770429">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1770429)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1770429">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aburr" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1299372); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1299372&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610225573" alt="Aburr" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1299372)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aburr" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1299372); return false;" >Aburr</a></span> <span class="odate time_1368132685 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 May 2013 20:51</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1770429">
									

<p>I have to say, I think that this is one of the cleanest, most well-executed things I've read on this site. Your voice is crisp and authoritative enough to make what could have otherwise been a tedious first act set-up interesting in itself, and the way that grounding naturally progresses through to MCD's increasingly ominous behavior is perfectly understated, even as the doings become at times almost comically gothic. The plotting is a bit stock and predictable from the outset, but that's never really a problem; you pace it well enough that it never gets stale, and that stock narrative, when framed through Gradley's uneasy rationalization of MCD as just another criminal rich boy's club, actually ends up producing good tension in itself. Which brings me to the portrayal of MCD, which I love. It really feels organic, here, not the hyperbolic nightmare market it's usually described as but a natural part of the landscape&#8212;which, since it of course still <em>is</em> a hyperbolic nightmare market, makes for a very interesting reflection on that landscape. I got a very American Psycho vibe from the whole thing, not least with the specificity of detail when discussing the cuisine and the cars everybody was driving. Some seven-paragraph descriptions of what kinds of suits people were wearing would've nailed that home, but, admittedly, maybe not done wonders for the flow.</p>
<p>This is a damn fine piece of work, dude, and you should be seriously proud of it. Great stuff.</p>

							</div>

								
					
